In the early hours of February 7, the official Weibo Account of Wuhan Central Hospital announced that Li Wenliang, an ophthalmologist at our hospital, had contracted pneumonia during the fight against COVID-19 infection, and all efforts to save him were futile, at 2:58 a.m. on February 7,2020, our deepest sympathies and condolences.

Li Wenliang, an ophthalmologist at Wuhan Central Hospital, became infected during an outbreak of COVID-19 pneumonia, but his condition deteriorated and rescue efforts were unsuccessful, the Wuhan Health Commission said on its website Monday, died at 2:58 a.m. on February 7,2020. I would like to express my deep condolences to Dr. Li Wenliang and my deepest condolences to his family!

On the afternoon of December 30,2019, Li Wenliang mentioned in a group of classmates that "seven cases of SARS have been confirmed in the south China fruit and seafood market" . "The latest news is that the coronavirus infection has been confirmed and virus typing is under way. ". On January 1,2020, the Wuhan Police issued a notice saying that some netizens had posted and reposted false information on the Internet without verification, causing adverse social impact. The Public Security Bureau, which investigated and verified the case, summoned eight offenders and dealt with them in accordance with the law. Two days later, Li Wenliang received a letter of caution from the police, who determined that the statement that "seven cases of SARS have been confirmed in the south China fruit and Seafood Market" was untrue.

Li Wenliang was treated in the intensive care unit of Wuhan Central Hospital on Jan. 12 for fever and cough by inhalation. On February 1,2020, Li Wenliang was diagnosed with COVID-19 pneumonia. "The result of nucleic acid test is positive today, the dust has settled and the diagnosis has finally been confirmed, " he said on his microblog.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
━━━━━

82-year-old patient with eye disease presented with cough and fever

According to Li Wenliang, he was treated for new coronavirus pneumonia, January 10 began to cough symptoms, 11 fever, 12 hospitalized. "At the time I was wondering why the bulletin was still saying there was no human-to-human transmission, no hospital-acquired infections. "

In an interview with the media, Li described how he caught pneumonia:

"On January 8, I saw an 82-year-old woman with acute angle-closure Glaucoma, and I was careless because we didn't have any special protection and she didn't have a fever.

But the next day, the 9th, she had a fever. By the time she's done with the C.T. , I'm GonNa have a strong suspicion that she's a viral pneumonia. Because the CT showed that her symptoms were "double lung ground-glass Lesion, " which is a sign of viral pneumonia. Also, we've ruled out common viral infections, mycoplasmas, Chlamydia infection, et CETERA. However, because the hospital did not have a test kit for the confirmed patient, she was not diagnosed at the time.

She was hospitalized on January 8, and I developed a cough on January 10. I then developed severe symptoms and was admitted to the intensive-care unit."

He has been in Wuhan's Central Hospital for intensive-care unit treatment since January 24. "after treatment and a recent test, I tested negative for nucleic acid, but I still have difficulty breathing and can not move. My parents are also in hospital, " Li Wenliang said on Weibo on Jan. 31.

Li Wenliang said, in the ward, he also saw many netizens support and encourage, the mood will be more relaxed, thank you for your support. "I would like to make it very clear that I have not lost my license. Please rest assured that I will actively cooperate with the treatment and try to get out of hospital as soon as possible. "

On Feb. 1, Li Wenliang revealed on his microblog that his nucleic acid test was positive. "The dust has settled, and the diagnosis has finally been confirmed. "

He was admonished by the Wuhan Public Security Department for Publishing information about the Wuhan epidemic

Li Wenliang recalled on Weibo that on December 30, he saw a test report of a patient who had tested positive for SARS coronavirus with high confidence. Since his classmates were also clinicians, he posted a message in the group saying "7 cases of SARS were confirmed" in order to remind students to pay attention to protection. After the message was sent, on January 3, the Public Security Bureau found Li Wenliang and signed a letter of reprimand. It's been working fine ever since.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
According to media reports, there were three medical communication groups released relevant information. In the early days of the epidemic, this information was not given enough attention. On January 1, Wuhan Police issued a notice: Some netizens have posted and reposted false information on the Internet without verification, causing adverse social impact. The investigation confirmed that the Public Security Bureau had summoned eight offenders and dealt with them in accordance with the law.

January 28th, "If we mechanically understand the applicable law, we can indeed conclude that, in view of the fact that the new type of pneumonia is not SARS, to say that SARS has appeared in Wuhan is to fabricate false information, and that the information has caused chaos in social order, and that the act of fabricating and spreading false information, in accordance with the law, is punishable by disciplinary or administrative punishment or even criminal punishment, " the Supreme People's Court said of the incident

"But it turns out that even though the new pneumonia was not SARS, the content of what was published by the publishers was not a complete fabrication. If the public had listened to this 'rumor' and taken measures such as wearing masks, strict disinfection and avoiding going to wildlife markets in response to the SARS scare, it would have been a blessing for us to better prevent and control new forms of pneumonia today. "

"As long as the information is basically true, the publishers and disseminators do not have malicious intentions and do not cause serious harm objectively, we should maintain a tolerant attitude towards such 'false information' . "

On December 31,2019, the Health Department of Wuhan City issued a circular on the epidemic situation of pneumonia. Subsequently, a number of Internet users reported someone on the Internet to post false information. In order to find out the situation, the Public Security Bureau has investigated and verified eight perpetrators. According to the investigation, eight people sent unverified information, such as "x hospital has confirmed more than one SARS case" , "confirmed 7 SARS cases" and "Y hospital has received a family of three from a certain state, and then suspected SARS" . According to the relevant provisions of the Law of the People's Republic of China on administrative penalties for public security, the circumstances of the above eight persons were extremely minor. At that time, the Public Security Bureau conducted education and criticism respectively, and none of them was given the punishments of warning, fine or detention.
